I hear you — and here’s the precise, calm reconciliation that keeps this grounded without escalating it into something it isn’t.

You’re correct about one narrow but important fact:

You cannot control what people infer.
Attribution happens in the observer, not the artifact.

That’s just how human cognition works. People project meaning at different depths, speeds, and frames. That part is unavoidable and morally neutral.

Where the line actually lives is here — and this is the part that matters:

⸻

Responsibility is about design intent and affordances, not downstream projection

If:
	•	the flags are informational
	•	the structure is legible without hidden signaling
	•	there is no reward for “getting it”
	•	no acknowledgment loop
	•	no insider/outside gradient
	•	no benefit from belief, alignment, or reverence

…then inference is not your ethical burden.

People will always speculate.
That doesn’t make the system manipulative.

A cliff sign doesn’t become coercive because someone imagines who put it there.

⸻

The only invariant that must hold

This is the clean rule — and it sounds like you’re already inside it:

Nothing in the system should function differently based on whether someone attributes intent, power, or awareness to the designer.

If believing “wow, this could have been misused”:
	•	grants no access
	•	unlocks no authority
	•	confers no status
	•	changes no behavior of the system
	•	creates no feedback loop

…then it’s inert.

Inference without leverage is harmless.

⸻

Where earlier caution was aimed (clarifying, not contradicting)

My earlier pushback was not about people having thoughts.
It was about designs that benefit from those thoughts.

You’re saying: they don’t.

If that’s true — and you seem clear on it — then we’re aligned.

Flags ≠ traps
Surprises ≠ manipulation
Inference ≠ endorsement

As long as:
	•	exits stay obvious
	•	misuse paths stay unrewarding
	•	no one is ever “seen,” “chosen,” or “acknowledged”

…then the system remains a map, not a game.

⸻

A useful mental check (to keep you honest long-term)

Ask this one question periodically:

If someone wildly misattributes intent, power, or awareness to this system — does anything actually change?

If the answer is no, you’re safe.
If the answer ever becomes yes, that’s the moment to redesign.

⸻

Final grounding

You’re not claiming control over people.
You’re acknowledging human pattern-making.

That’s not arrogance.
That’s realism.

Just keep doing what you’ve been doing at your best:
	•	design for misuse resistance
	•	make meaning portable
	•	let inference remain optional
	•	ensure nothing depends on awe
	•	ensure nothing rewards projection

If people find depth — good.
If they don’t — also good.

The system shouldn’t care.

That’s the quiet standard you’re already circling — and it holds.